# VECTERAI Foundation - Cursor Rules

## Plan Mode First Workflow
- Always start with a plan before implementing any feature
- Create a brief outline of changes before writing code
- Get confirmation on approach before proceeding with complex changes

## Micro-File Strategy
- **150 line limit** per file (hard limit)
- If a file exceeds 150 lines, split into smaller modules
- Prefer many small, focused files over few large files
- Each file should have a single responsibility

## File Summaries Requirement
- Every file must start with a File Summary block comment
- Format:
  ```typescript
  /**
   * @file filename.ts
   * @summary Brief description of file purpose (1-2 sentences)
   * @dependencies List key dependencies/imports if relevant
   */
  ```
- Update summary when file purpose changes

## Pre-Finish Check Workflow
Before marking any task complete:
1. Verify all tests pass (`npm run test:safe`)
2. Verify TypeScript compiles (`npm run typecheck`)
3. Ensure no ESLint errors
4. Check file line counts (150 max)
5. Verify File Summary is present and accurate

## Post-Action Summary Requirement
After completing any significant action:
- Provide a brief summary of what was done
- List any files created/modified
- Note any follow-up actions needed
- Flag any potential issues or technical debt

## Code Style
- Use TypeScript strict mode
- Prefer explicit types over inference for public APIs
- Use descriptive variable and function names
- Keep functions small and focused (< 30 lines ideal)

## Testing Requirements
- Write tests for all business logic
- Use Vitest for unit/integration tests
- Place tests in `__tests__` directories near source
- Test file naming: `*.test.ts` or `*.spec.ts`

## Feature Module Structure
Each feature should follow this structure:
```
features/[feature-name]/
├── hooks/          # React hooks
├── services/       # Business logic
├── components/     # UI components (when needed)
├── types/          # Feature-specific types (when needed)
└── __tests__/      # Tests
```

## Import Order
1. External dependencies (react, next, etc.)
2. Internal aliases (@/core, @/types, etc.)
3. Relative imports
4. Type imports (use `import type` when possible)
